SIMPLE: spinster
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spinster
<hw>Spin"ster</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Spin</ets> +
<ets>-ster</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A woman who spins, or whose
occupation is to spin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She spake to <qex>spinster</qex> to spin it out.</q>
<rj><qau>Piers Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>spinsters</qex> and the knitters in the sun.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A man who spins.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An unmarried or single woman; --
used in legal proceedings as a title, or addition to the
surname.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If a gentlewoman be termed a <qex>spinster</qex>, she may abate
the writ.</q> <rj><qau>Coke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A woman of evil life and character; -- so called
from being forced to spin in a house of correction.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spinstress</ent>⟦br⟧
